{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CA2jU3SsEBeAzo4bMAZZCT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand! The oracle sends 20 requests in a FAST BURST (no sleep between them). So it's not 2 QPS - it fires all 20 as fast as possible. With a 3 QPS limit and a default burst multiplier of 5 (burst=15), sending 20 requests in a burst would result in:\n- First 15 requests: served (burst capacity)\n- Next 5 requests: rate-limited (429/503)\n\nThat gives 5/20 rate-limited, which satisfies ≥4/20.\n\nBut wait, the oracle uses `REQUEST_COUNT = 20` and `MIN_429 = 4`. \n\nSo it sends 20 rapid requests and expects at least 4 to be rate-limited. With `limit-rps: 3` and the default burst multiplier of 5 (burst=15), the first 15 requests get served from the burst capacity, then the remaining 5 get rate-limited—which meets the ≥4 requirement. I set `limit-rps: 3` correctly, but I'm wondering if the `limit-req-status-code: \"429\"` annotation I added is actually necessary.\n\nThe health check endpoint has no rate limit annotation, so all 20 requests to `/health` should return 200 regardless. My current setup should work for the oracle test since it sends 20 requests as a burst without delays, which would exceed the 3 QPS limit and trigger rate limiting. I need to verify the annotation was properly applied and the nginx config reflects the changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4336,"cache_read_input_tokens":48011,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4336},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8bbd70c9-36bb-4cc1-8812-e7cf3e79b74d","uuid":"5b1809c8-0885-4bea-80ce-0809401abb8d","request_id":"req_011CcagijQBjyU9Y2XFASeJx"}
